50|$|<b>Land</b> <b>governance</b> is {{concerned}} with issues of land ownership and tenure. It consists of the policies, processes and institutions by which decisions about the access to, use of and control over land are made, implemented and enforced; it is also about managing and reconciling competing claims on land. In developing countries, it is relevant {{as a tool to}} contribute to equitable and sustainable development, addressing the phenomenon that is known as ‘land grabbing’. The operational dimension of <b>land</b> <b>governance</b> is land administration.|$|E
50|$|At {{various times}} the Secretary of State for Canada was {{responsible}} for the Royal Canadian Mounted Police, the civil service, the Queen's Printer for Canada, administration of Crown <b>lands,</b> <b>governance</b> of Canadian Indians (as they were called) as well as various ceremonial and state duties. Generally, any government role and responsibility which was not specifically assigned to a cabinet minister would be the de facto responsibility of the Secretary of State.|$|R
